The paper deals with the analysis of the uplink of a massive MIMO network using stochastic geometry. This involves modeling the locations of base stations as a Poisson point process, which falls under the category of network science (cs.NI). The use of pilot sequences for reducing interference due to pilot contamination is a common technique in information theory (cs.IT). The analysis of signal-to-interference-and-noise ratio (SINR) coverage probability and average spectral efficiency (SE) involves the use of probability theory and statistics, which falls under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). The use of massive MIMO systems involves the use of multiple antennas, which falls under the category of multimedia (cs.MM). Finally, the use of stochastic geometry for modeling the locations of base stations and users involves the use of geometric tools, which falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.GT).
